  <h2>Architecture</h2>
  <div class="arch-block">
    Patient App / Pharmacy Backend<br />
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;│<br />
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;▼<br />
    SQL ETL layer (Python) ──→ GA4 BigQuery Export<br />
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;│&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;│<br />
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;▼&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;▼<br />
    Power BI DirectQuery ←────── Acquisition Model<br />
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;│<br />
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;├── Pharmacy Owner Dashboard (Rx, Delivery, Consultations)<br />
    &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;└── Growth Executive View (Acquisition, Cohorts, Attribution)
  </div>

  <h2>What broke / what I'd change</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Data freshness vs. model complexity.</strong> DirectQuery gives live data but puts pressure on query performance: a few complex DAX measures caused slow loads on the pharmacy owner view before I rewrote them as pre-aggregated SQL views. The lesson: push complexity upstream (SQL) not downstream (DAX) wherever the model allows.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>NHS calendar edge cases</strong> surfaced late. Prescription volumes drop sharply over bank holiday periods in ways that initially made SLA metrics look anomalous. Adding calendar dimension logic to flag NHS non-working periods was obvious in retrospect, and should be part of any health-data modelling checklist.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Self-serve adoption.</strong> The dashboards were adopted well by the operations team but pharmacy owners needed more onboarding than expected. Next version would embed contextual tooltips directly in the Power BI views and include a short walkthrough video. Analytics only creates value if the people it's built for actually use it.
  </p>

</CaseStudy>
